docs.abstract: OpenAI, now managed by start-up guru Sam Altman, wants to create a machine that can do anything the human brain can do. Skeptics wonder if it is possible.

docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — As the waitress approached the table, Sam Altman held up his phone. That made it easier to see the dollar amount typed into an investment contract he had spent the last 30 days negotiating with Microsoft.

headline.main: With $1 Billion From Microsoft, an A.I. Lab Wants to Mimic the Brain
headline.print_headline: $1 Billion in Hand, A.I. Lab Wants to Mimic the Brain

docs.abstract: It’s not the first self-driving bike. But equipped with an A.I. chip, it may be the nearest to thinking for itself.
docs.snippet: It’s not the first self-driving bike. But equipped with an A.I. chip, it may be the nearest to thinking for itself.
docs.lead_paragraph: As corporate giants like Ford, G.M. and Waymo struggle to get their self-driving cars on the road, a team of researchers in China is rethinking autonomous transportation using a souped-up bicycle.

headline.main: And Now, a Bicycle Built for None
headline.print_headline: Self-Driving Bike Glides Toward the Future of A.I.

docs.abstract: The company, long a target of President Trump, is seen as the leading competitor for a $10 billion cloud computing contract that the president said he was “getting tremendous complaints about.”
docs.snippet: The company, long a target of President Trump, is seen as the leading competitor for a $10 billion cloud computing contract that the president said he was “getting tremendous complaints about.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump said on Thursday that he was looking “very seriously” at intervening in the hard-fought commercial battle for a $10 billion Pentagon cloud computing contract for which Amazon, a company he has frequently attacked, is seen as the leading contender.

headline.main: Trump Says He May Intervene in Huge Pentagon Contract Sought by Amazon
headline.print_headline: Pentagon Bid Pits Amazon Against Trump

docs.abstract: The strong results indicate large companies are still investing in new technology, shrugging off concerns of a downturn or trade war.

docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — If you followed Congress’s scrutiny of the technology industry this week, you would think that Amazon, Google and Facebook are the biggest tech companies around. But Microsoft is the sector’s quiet giant. It is not only the largest tech company, but it is the largest publicly traded company of any kind, with a market capitalization of more than $1 trillion.

headline.main: Microsoft Earnings: Sales Jump 12 Percent, Fueled by Cloud
headline.print_headline: Microsoft Earnings Continue to Climb Higher on the Cloud

docs.abstract: Large databases, built with images from social networks and dating services, contain millions of pictures of people’s faces. Some are shared worldwide.
docs.snippet: Large databases, built with images from social networks and dating services, contain millions of pictures of people’s faces. Some are shared worldwide.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Dozens of databases of people’s faces are being compiled without their knowledge by companies and researchers, with many of the images then being shared around the world, in what has become a vast ecosystem fueling the spread of facial recognition technology.

headline.main: Facial Recognition Tech Is Growing Stronger, Thanks to Your Face
headline.print_headline: Quietly Hoarding Millions of Faces Culled From Web

docs.abstract: It’s time for lawmakers to step back in, carefully.
docs.snippet: It’s time for lawmakers to step back in, carefully.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tech regulation may be the only thing on which a polarized Capitol Hill can agree. “We should be suing Google and Facebook and all that, and perhaps we will,” President Trump recently declared. Senator Elizabeth Warren, a Democratic presidential candidate, has made the breakup of tech companies a central plank of her campaign. Even Silicon Valley-friendly contenders like Pete Buttigieg have called for curbs on the industry’s power.

headline.main: Letting the Internet Regulate Itself Was a Good Idea — in the 1990s

docs.abstract: Companies like Microsoft see a multibillion-dollar opportunity to get more personal technology to workers who don’t sit behind a desk.
docs.snippet: Companies like Microsoft see a multibillion-dollar opportunity to get more personal technology to workers who don’t sit behind a desk.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHILLICOTHE, Ohio — When Toby Bouska Jr. started assembling cabs for Kenworth semitrucks last year, he learned the ropes by observing longtime workers at the factory. But it wasn’t exactly engaging, and he didn’t get much practice doing the job himself.

headline.main: You’re Hired. Now Wear This Headset to Learn the Job.
headline.print_headline: Tech Tools for the Factory Floor
